Retrieval Augmented Generation:
    "Retrieval Augmented Generation"... or "RAG" for short. 
    Applications need search, and in the age of AI, search has become a lot better, 
    but also a bit more complex


RAG and CONTEXT ENGINEERING is the next step in search after semantic search.

What Is Search?
    Filtering data and finding info that match certain conditions.

    Search is a non-negotiable feature of nearly all content-based web applications. In this course, we'll learn a bit about how it works, but more specifically:
         we'll focus on how to use AI and LLMs and search features together for an even better user experience. There is so much more to a good search experience than exact keyword matches. We want to be able to:
            Find relevant results even if the search terms don't match exactly
            Match based on semantic meaning, not just keywords
            Understand user intent and context
            Provide succinct results that go beyond the raw data


To do so, we'll be learning about RAG, or "Retrieval Augmented Generation." And "retrieval" is the first component in RAG:

    R: Retrieve(find or extract (information stored in a computer).) information via a search algorithm
    A: Augment(make (something) greater by adding to it; increase.) our instructions with the search results
    G: Generate better, richer, and more accurate information using LLMs

